{{Infobox video game | title = Sophie's World | released = 1997 | genre = Educational, Adventure }}
'''''Sophie's World''''' is a 1997 educational adventure game developed by The MultiMedia Corporation and published by Voyager. it is an adaption of the novel [[Sophie's World]], written by Norwegian writer Jostein Gaarder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.justadventure.com/reviews/Sophies_World/Sophie.shtm|title=Review:|date=2001-08-09|access-date=2018-02-24|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010809001410/http://www.justadventure.com/reviews/Sophies_World/Sophie.shtm|archivedate=2001-08-09|df=}}</ref>
== Development == The game was developed by a small team of 6-7 core MAC developers and Win32 developers, 1 lead graphic designer, and producers, as well as contract workers. The scenes, audio, and timelines were collaborated between the departments. Sam Deane created a game engine from scratch to present the scenes. Simon Jenkins wrote the natural language engine for the in-game instant message application. The writing was aided by academics of philosophy to ensure realism and accuracy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RyWIRwOuyR0&lc=UghCUYBmqCFInXgCoAEC|title=Conversation between developers Alan McAuley, Simon Jenkins, and Sam Deane in the comments section of a YouTube Letsplay of their game|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>
== Plot and gameplay == The player explores philosophical concepts through the eyes of the 14 year old Sophie. The title contains an in-game encyclopaedic database.
== Critical reception == Ray Ivey of Just Adventure described it as short, imaginative, and delicious.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.justadventure.com/reviews/Sophies_World/Sophie.shtm|title=Review:|date=2001-08-09|access-date=2018-02-24|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010809001410/http://www.justadventure.com/reviews/Sophies_World/Sophie.shtm|archivedate=2001-08-09|df=}}</ref> Quandaryland's Steve Ramsey wrote that while the game only took an hor to complete, he didn't have a desire to stay in the world for longer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.quandaryland.com/jsp/dispArticle.jsp?index=497|title=Sophie's World Review by Quandary|date=2007-06-08|access-date=2018-02-24|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070608102108/http://www.quandaryland.com/jsp/dispArticle.jsp?index=497|archivedate=2007-06-08|df=}}</ref>
At the 1997 Bima Awards, the British Interactive Multimedia Association presented the game with a craft award for sound and music.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/winners-of1997-bima-awards-announced-1256332.html|title=Winners of1997 Bima awards announced|date=1997-06-17|work=The Independent|access-date=2018-02-24|language=en-GB}}</ref>
